SIMPLE: obsession
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Obsession
<hw>Ob*ses"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>obsessio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>obsession</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of besieging.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark>
<rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being besieged; -- used specifically of
a person beset by a spirit from without.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark>
<rj><au>Tylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whether by <qex>obsession</qex> or possession, I will not
determine.</q> <rj><qau>Burton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An excessive preoccupation of the thoughts or
feelings; the persistent haunting or domination of the mind by a
particular desire, idea, or image.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Any driving motive; a
compelling goal; -- not necessarily implying a negative judgment, as
does sense 3; <as>as, the coach was <ex>obsessed</ex> with winning the
state championship</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Something that causes an obsession{3}.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The state of being obsessed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>obsessive</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>obsessional</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>
